 fees and charges in connection with a license for the\r\nApplication Server 7 Standard Edition, the additional terms and\r\nconditions found in this Section I apply in addition to the Base\r\nAgreement. Capitalized terms not defined herein shall have the\r\nmeanings ascribed to them in the Base Agreement. These terms shall\r\nsupersede any inconsistent or conflicting terms in the Base\r\nAgreement.  1. Additional Features\r\n\r\nYou may use the Standard Edition Features solely for internal\r\ndevelopment.\r\n\r\n2.  No Production Use.  You have no right to use the Standard\r\nEdition Features in an internally accessible or externally\r\naccessible production environment, for commercial use, or for\r\noperational purposes.  Nor may you use the Standard Edition Features\r\nfor staging or quality assurance purposes. For the purposes of this\r\nsection, quality assurance and staging involves exposing instance(s)\r\nof Software to end users and/or testers for testing an application\r\nprior to production, or staging an application prior to production.\r\nIf you wish to deploy Software in a production environment or for\r\ntesting and quality assurance purposes, you must do one of the\r\nfollowing:  a. disable the Standard Edition Features using the\r\nPlatform Edition key; or b. purchase a license for the Application\r\nServer 7 Standard Edition. In that event, the  terms and conditions\r\nfound in Section II (below) apply.\r\n\r\n\r\nSection II:  Secondary Supplemental Terms for SunTM ONE Application\r\nServer 7 Standard Edition Update 2\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you have paid in full all corresponding fees and charges in\r\nconnection with a license for the Application Server 7 Standard\r\nEdition Update 2, the additional terms and conditions found in this\r\nSection II apply in addition to the Base License.  Capitalized terms\r\nnot defined herein shall have the meanings ascribed to them in the\r\nBase Agreement. These terms shall supersede any inconsistent or\r\nconflicting terms in the Base Agreement.\r\n\r\n1.      Definitions.\r\n\r\n\tA.   \"Application(s)\" means a unit of software deployed in\r\n\tthe form of a J2EE Enterprise Archive (EAR) file or as a\r\n\tJ2EE module.  A J2EE module is either a Web Archive (WAR)\r\n\tfile or an EJB JAR file.\r\n\r\n\tB.      \"Designated CPU(s)\" means the single central\r\n\tprocessing unit (\"CPU\") upon which Software is executed.\r\n\r\n\tC.      \"Entry(ies)\" means a representation of a single\r\n\tconceptual or real-world object stored in the directory\r\n\tserver contained in the DSS (as defined below) which has a\r\n\tdistinguished name that is unique in your enterprise.\r\n\r\n\r\n2.  Additional Features\r\n\r\nYou may use (including in a production environment) Software with or\r\nwithout the Standard Edition Features enabled only on the number of\r\nDesignated CPU(s) for which you have paid the corresponding fee for\r\nsuch usage.  Software may be installed on a computer system with\r\nmore CPUs than the number licensed if (i) the corresponding\r\nadditional fees are paid prior to such installation and you provide\r\nSun with the make, model, operating system and number of CPUs of the\r\nnew or reconfigured system or (ii) Software cannot access or use\r\nCPUs for which you have not paid the corresponding fees.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSunONE/Application Server7 PE/SEU2 02JUN03/HBF\r\n\r\n", notes: "estratto da: https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/software/page/eupl/eupl-compatible-open-source-licences#section-3\r\n\r\nIn Europe, lawyers (i.e. Till Jaeger in OSI licence discussions, September 2013) understanding of the directive is that software, that is independently created and exchanges information with other software through an interface, is independent software and not a derivative work. The directive permits reproduction of the portion of code (data formats, APIs) that are necessary for implementing this interoperability. From the perspective of European copyright law, the Court of Justice of the European Union will therefore (most probably) consider that linking software for interoperability (= for exchanging information) makes no derivatives and that the way of linking (statically producing a single binary or dynamic at runtime) is a technical modality without substantial importance regarding copyright. On this specific point, the European copyright law contradicts the perspective of the GPLv2 (because of the wording of sec. 2 GPLv2), while on other points the GPL was validated by European courts.", similar_license_id: 101},
