  {name: "customfield", version: "1.0.0", title: "jira-pocketknife-customfield", description: "This library (and reference plugin) provides the framework for best-practice CRUD management of ActiveObjects backed data in JIRA plugins. It could be generalised for all Atlassian plugins, but for now depends on JIRA-specific artefacts. \r\n\r\nThe library contains a number of generic interfaces representing 4-tier data management.\r\n\r\n* ActiveObjectsDao - a model DAO layer over ActiveObjects.\r\n* Manager - a permission ignoring manager layer over the ActiveObjectsDao. Ideally, caching should live here.\r\n* Service - a permission checking service layer over the Manager.\r\n* Resource - a RESTful layer \r\n\r\nEach interface has a simple-case generic abstract implementation (and some have specializations for handling relational mapping). For each AO-backed data type, you will need three representations:\r\n\r\n* An interface extending Entity, representing the AO itself. This must be added to your <ao> entry in your atlassian-plugin.xml.\r\n* A class extending AbstractModel, which must be made immutable (such that it can be stored in a cache).\r\n* A class extending Entry, which must be marshallable by Jersey (ie: annotated with javax.xml.bind.annotation.*). \r\n\r\nTo add a new vertical, begin by creating a class which extends GenericCRUDResource. This will need to be specialized around your Model and Entry classes. Your constructor will require a Service typed on your Model class, so go ahead and create one, extending GenericPermissionCheckingService. This will require you to implement a number of permission related abstract methods, as well as a Manager typed on your model. Once again create one, extending GenericCacheHoldingManager using your AO Entity as the second type parameter. The only abstract method is for error generation, though there are protected methods which you can override from GenericCacheHoldingManager to use as hooks for handling relational mappings. Your manager's constructor will require an ActiveObjectsDao and an AOMapper. In the simplest case, extend GenericActiveObjectsDao in the former case, and implement AOMapper in the latter. Your Dao should require nothing beyond being typed on your AO. Your AOMapper will require you to implement 3 methods relating your model to your AO Entity. Once this is done, you will need to register your Dao, AOMapper, Manager and Service with spring to make the constructor injectable (easiest with atlassian-plugin.xml <component> tags, though you can manage your own spring.xml if you swing that way). Finally, you will need to create an atlassian-plugin.xml <rest> entry for your Resource. You can now spin up your plugin and test your REST resource out through the developer toolbox (underneath the user-dropdown). \r\n\r\nWatch the repository for any future updates.\r\n", license_id: 3, use_id: 1, checked_at: "2014-03-11", result: true, notes: "Licenza\r\nhttps://bitbucket.org/jhatherly/pocketknife/src/f3707900365fe4a6117f0d3c238e40701f254196/LICENSE?at=master\r\n\r\n", purchased: false, own: false, leave_out: false},
